        <name>19.2.5.8 Solving an Exact Equation Ex5</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Is the equation \(x^{{@aa@}}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} + {@(aa+1)*x^(aa-1)@}y = {@bb@}x^3\) exact? [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;

    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Multiply \(x^{{@aa@}}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} + {@(aa+1)*x^(aa-1)@}y&amp;nbsp; = {@bb@}x^3\) by \(x\) and show that the resulting equation is exact and obtain its solution.&lt;/p&gt;

        &lt;p&gt;Exact form: \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x} \bigg(\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]&amp;nbsp; \(\bigg) = {@bb@}x^4\).&amp;nbsp;[[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;

        &lt;p&gt;\(y =\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] \( + \dfrac{C}{x^4}\). [[feedback:prt3]] &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;We are given the equation \(x^{{@aa@}}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} + {@(aa+1)*x^(aa-1)@}y&amp;nbsp; = {@bb@}x^3\). It cannot be written in the form \[ f(x) \dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} + y f^{\prime}(x) = g(x).\] Therefore it is not exact.&lt;/p&gt; 
	&lt;/li&gt;
  
  &lt;li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Multiplying the equation by \(x\) yields the equation \(x^{{@aa+1@}}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} + {@aa+1@}x^{{@aa@}}y = {@bb@}x^4.\)&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;The equation is of an exact form since it can be written as \[ f(x) \dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} + y f^{\prime}(x) = g(x)\] with \[f(x) = x^{{@aa+1@}} \quad \text{and} \quad g(x)={@bb@}x^4.\] Hence the exact form becomes \[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}(yf(x))
    = g(x), \quad \text{i.e} \quad \dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}(yx^{{@aa+1@}}) = {@bb@}x^4.\]&lt;/p&gt;
    
    &lt;p&gt;Integrating both sides gives \[ yx^{{@aa+1@}} = \int {@bb@}x^4 \ \mathrm{d}x\] which implies  \[yx^{{@aa+1@}} = \dfrac{{@bb@}}{5}x^5 + C.\] Rearranging to find \(y\) we get \[y = {@(bb/5)*x^(5-aa-1)@} + \dfrac{C}{x^{{@aa+1@}}}.\]&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
